Problem Statement¶

For this problem, given a group selfie/photo, we are required to count the number of heads present in the picture. The primary aim of face detection algorithms is to determine whether there is any face in an image or not.

  • To develop an initial answer to your question
    The method of face detection in pictures is complicated because of variability present across human faces such as pose, expression, position and orientation, skin colour, the presence of glasses or facial hair, differences in camera gain, lighting conditions, and image resolution. However, recent advancements in field has made the objects detection feasible using deep learning. We are going to use available open source libraries to implement this project.

  • To determine whether the question you are asking can be answered by the data you have collected
    The above problem can be addressed using Deep Learning. We have collected adequate data to develop a model and produce the predictions of the face counts in a given image.

  • To determine if there are any problems with your dataset
    There is no problem with dataset or the images gathered to perfrom the tasks. Below is the basic exploratory image analysis.

Simple Thresholding¶

Here, we are going to use OpenCV library mainly aimed at real-time computer vision. Thresholding is a very popular segmentation technique, used for separating an object considered as a foreground from its background. A threshold is a value which has two regions on its either side i.e. below the threshold or above the threshold.
The function cv2.threshold is used to apply the thresholding. The first argument is the source image, which should be a grayscale image. The second argument is the threshold value which is used to classify the pixel values. The third argument is the maximum value which is assigned to pixel values exceeding the threshold. OpenCV provides different types of thresholding which is given by the fourth parameter of the function. Below are the differnt types of thresholdings.

In [10]:
first_cv = cv2.imread("E:\\Face_Count\\train_HNzkrPW (1)\\train\\10436.jpg",0)
#first_cv = cv2.cvtColor(first_cv, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
_, th1 = cv2.threshold(first_cv, 50, 255, cv2.THRESH_BINARY)
_, th2 = cv2.threshold(first_cv, 50, 255, cv2.THRESH_BINARY_INV)
_, th3 = cv2.threshold(first_cv, 50, 255, cv2.THRESH_TOZERO)
_, th4 = cv2.threshold(first_cv, 50, 255, cv2.THRESH_TOZERO_INV)
_, th5 = cv2.threshold(first_cv, 50, 255, cv2.THRESH_TRUNC)
titles = ["Original Image", "BINARY", "BINARY_INV", "TOZERO", "TOZERO_INV", "TRUNC"]
images = [first_cv, th1, th2, th3, th4, th5]
plt.figure(figsize= (15,7))
for i in range(6):
    plt.subplot(2,3,i+1), plt.imshow(images[i], 'gray')
    plt.title(titles[i])
    plt.xticks([]), plt.yticks([])
plt.show()

Another Thresholding technique is Adaptive Thresholding. Simple Thresholding, a global value of threshold was used which remained constant throughout. So, a constant threshold value won’t help in the case of variable lighting conditions in different areas. Adaptive thresholding is the method where the threshold value is calculated for smaller regions. This leads to different threshold values for different regions with respect to the change in lighting.

In [11]:
_, th1 = cv2.threshold(first_cv, 127, 255, cv2.THRESH_BINARY)
th2 = cv2.adaptiveThreshold(first_cv, 255, cv2.ADAPTIVE_THRESH_MEAN_C, \
                               cv2.THRESH_BINARY, 11, 2)
th3 = cv2.adaptiveThreshold(first_cv, 255, cv2.ADAPTIVE_THRESH_GAUSSIAN_C,\
                                cv2.THRESH_BINARY, 11, 2)
titles = ['Original Image', 'Global Thresholding (v = 127)',
            'Adaptive Mean Thresholding', 'Adaptive Gaussian Thresholding']
images = [first_cv, th1, th2, th3]
plt.figure(figsize= (10,7))
for i in range(4):
    plt.subplot(2,2,i+1),plt.imshow(images[i],'gray')
    plt.title(titles[i])
    plt.xticks([]),plt.yticks([])
plt.show()

In Otsu Thresholding, a value of the threshold isn’t chosen but is determined automatically. A bimodal image (two distinct image values) is considered. The histogram generated contains two peaks. So, a generic condition would be to choose a threshold value that lies in the middle of both the histogram peak values

In [12]:

plt.title("OSTU Threholding")
plt.show()

Histogram equalization is a method in image processing of contrast adjustment using the image’s histogram. This method usually increases the global contrast of many images, especially when the usable data of the image is represented by close contrast values. Through this adjustment, the intensities can be better distributed on the histogram. This allows for areas of lower local contrast to gain a higher contrast.

In [13]:
sns.distplot(cv2.equalizeHist(first_cv), bins = 12)
plt.title("Equalized Histogram")
plt.show()
In [14]:
plt.imshow(cv2.equalizeHist(first_cv))
plt.title("Equalized Image")
plt.show()

Edge Detection¶

Canny Edge Detection is a popular edge detection algorithm. Since edge detection is susceptible to noise in the image, first step is to remove the noise in the image with a 3*3 Gaussian filter. Below are the various image detectors.

In [29]:
canny = cv2.Canny(first_cv, 100, 200)
sobelx = cv2.Sobel(first_cv, cv2.CV_64F, 1, 0)
sobely = cv2.Sobel(first_cv, cv2.CV_64F, 0, 1)
SobelCombined = cv2.bitwise_and(sobelx, sobely)
lap = cv2.Laplacian(first_cv, cv2.CV_64F, ksize = 3)
lap = np.uint8(np.absolute(lap))
titles = ["Original Image", "Canny", "Sobel", "Laplacian"]
images = [first_cv, canny, SobelCombined, lap]
plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
for i in  range(4):
    plt.subplot(2, 2, i+1), plt.imshow(images[i], 'gray')
    plt.title(titles[i])
    plt.xticks([]), plt.yticks([])
plt.show()
